==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Schismatic
<hw>Schis*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧z*m⟦acr⟧t"⟦icr⟧k; <it>so nearly all
orthoepists</it>)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>schismaticus</ets>,
Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>schismatique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to
schism; implying schism; partaking of the nature of schism; tending to
schism; <as>as, <ex>schismatic</ex> opinions or
proposals</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Schismatic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Schismatic
<hw>Schis*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who
creates or takes part in schism; one who separates from an established
church or religious communion on account of a difference of
opinion.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧They were popularly classed together as canting
<xex>schismatics</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Heretic; partisan. See
<er>Heretic</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Schismatical</ent>⟦br⟧
